@tc<CH8>Customs of the Rosh Hashana Meal
@ex<ALD-4>On the first night of Rosh Hashana, it is customary to perform several symbolic
rituals, to serve as good omens for the coming new year. At the beginning of the
evening meal it is customary to dip a portion of the challah in honey and after
eating a piece, the weight of an olive, say: “@hh<HEB>‰¡„ ‰ ˜¢–í  Œ¡”¢‰ò õú¡‡£ƒŸõ ’¢ŒŸ‰å õ¢¢„ ˆí¢„
å¡šå—¢„@ee<ENG>ĞMay it be Your will to renew for us a good and sweet year.” Then, take a
piece of sweet apple and dip it in honey. First make the blessing, “@hh<HEB>á¢˜åç €£ú¢„ „' €›Œ¥„ŸÍ‰å
ÍŒç „¢’íŒ¢ áí˜Ÿ€ ô¡˜ ‰ „¢’Ÿ•@ee<ENG>ĞBlessed are You, Adonoy, our God, King of the universe, Who
creates the fruit of the tree.” After tasting it, repeat the above prayer, “@hh<HEB>‰¡„ ‰ ˜¢–í@ee<ENG>ĞMay
it be Your will to renew for us a good and sweet year.” It is also a custom to eat a
piece of the head of some animal, (preferably a sheep) and say: “@hh<HEB>‰¡„ ‰ ˜¢–í õ „¡‰„
Œ¡˜€õ@ee<ENG>ĞMay it be Your will that we be at the head.” We also eat certain vegetables,
the names of which convey the connotations of good fortune, such as carrots which
in Yiddish are called mehren (increase), and we say: “@hh<HEB>‰¡„ ‰ ˜¢–í õ‰ ˜¡áå †¡‹å‰íšŸ‰å@ee<ENG>ĞMay it be
Your will that our merits increase.”
