@ct<ENG>Kaddish d’Rabanan
@ex<EM><EN>Kaddish is not the name generally given to this prayer in the Talmud. It is
referred to there as “May His great Name<TIE>.<TIE>.<TIE>.”, because the congregational response
beginning with these words is the heart of this prayer. Only in one minor tractate,
(Maseches Soferim 16, 19, and 21) is it referred to as Kaddish.
@xe<EM><EN>Composed primarily in Aramaic, the language spoken and understood by most
Jews in the Second Temple period (See Tosafos to Maseches Berachos 3a), neverthe
less, several Hebrew phrases, which were familiar even to the unschooled, were
also incorporated in the prayer.
@xe<EM><EN>This particular form of Kaddish d’Rabanan, is so named because of the insertion
of the paragraph which begins with the words “Upon Yisrael and upon our Sages,
etc.” This Kaddish is recited following the study of Talmud or Midrash and invokes
God’s blessings on the Sages of Jewry, the transmitters of the Oral Torah.
