@ct<ENG>Sounding of the Shofar
@RU<GRA0.40><KV384.000>
@RU<WT1.5><KV384.000>
@saAccording to Rav Saadiah Gaon the Almighty commanded us to sound the
shofar on Rosh Hashana for these ten reasons:
@sa1) Rosh Hashana corresponds to the first day of creation and the shofar
proclaims the sovereignty of the Creator. We are obliged to coronate God as
King on this day in the manner written by Dovid, “@hh<HEB>á£‡–¥–¡˜íš …¡—íŒ õí”¢˜ „¢˜ ‰’å Œ ”¡Ÿ‰
„£îŒç „'@ee<ENG>, With trumpets and the sound of shofar, call out in the presence of
the King, Almighty” (Psalms 48:6).
@sa2) Rosh Hashana is the beginning of the Ten Days of Repentance and the
shofar calls the people to amend their lives before the final judgment of Yom
Kippur. It was customary for rulers to issue a final warning to their subjects
before punishing them for violating their decrees. Similarly, the shofar
represents God’s last warning to His people to repent.
@sa3) The sounding of the shofar recalls the revelation of the Torah on Mount
Sinai. The Torah was given to us amid blasts of the shofar, as it is written,
“@hh<HEB>…¡—íŒ õí”¢˜ ‡¢†¢— ¡€¥ƒ@ee<ENG>,” the sound of shofar was most powerful” (Shemos 19:16),
and the people accepted it saying “We will do and we will listen.”
@sa4) The shofar brings to mind the warnings and exhortations of the prophets
which are likened to the blasts of the shofar, as it is said, @hh<HEB>…¡õ¢£’ „£õ¥Ÿ’£ €š —íŒ
„£õí”¢˜ …¡Œ¥€  †¡„¢˜ …£ú¢í€ ‡˜ …£ú ÷¢‡Ÿ„å ƒ¢í á¡˜¥€õí ‰ „¡‰„ .<TIE>.<TIE>. …¡„å€  †¡„¢˜ £”¡õí  ŒŸˆ.@ee<ENG> He who hears
the sound of the shofar and does not take warning, the sword come ands
takes him away, his blood will be upon his own head .<TS>.<TS>. but he who heeds
warning will save his soul. (Yechezkel 33:4,5).
@sa5) The shofar reminds us of the destruction of the Holy Temple which was
destroyed amid the sounding of enemy trumpets, as it is said: @hh<HEB>ë ‰ —íŒ õí”¢˜
õ¢£’£ú¡ £”¡õ ‰ ú¡˜å’£š  Œ¡‡¢¢„@hh@ee<ENG>Ğ“For you have heard the sound of the shofar, O my
soul, the shouts of battle (Yirmiyahu 4:19); and when we hear the shofar on
Rosh Hashana, we pray to God to restore the Temple to its former glory.
@sa6) The shofar recalls the willingness of Yitzchak to be sacrificed on the altar
in obedience to God’s command to Avraham. We pray that with the sound
ing of the shofar his great deed will be recalled by the Almighty as a source
of merit to his descendents.
@sa7) It is the nature of the shofar’s sound to arouse the heart to awe and
reverence. Thus when we hear the shofar, we tremble and humble ourselves
before the presence of God.
@sa8) The shofar reminds us of the ultimate Day of Judgment, as it is said, “@hh<HEB>—¢˜í
‰í „' „£‚¢ƒíŒ, —¢˜í å£„Ÿ˜ ¡€¥ƒĞ‰í õí”¢˜ åš¡˜å’¢„@ee<ENG>” “The great day of Almighty is near,
it is near and rapidly approachingĞa day of the shofar and shouting”
(Tzefanyah 1:14, 16).
@sa9) The shofar inspires us with hope for the ultimate ingathering of our
people and their deliverance from exile, as it is said, “@hh<HEB>…¡„¢‰¢„ á£‰í „£„å€ ‰ ú¢—£’ á¡õí”¢˜
‚¢ƒíŒ å¢€å „¢€¥¡ƒ ‰ á¡€˜• €£õå˜ …‚…'@hh@ee<ENG> And it will be on that day that a great shofar will
be sounded; and those who were lost in the land of Ashur .<TS>.<TS>. will come and
prostrate themselves before Adonoy on the holy mountain in
Yerushalayim.” (Yeshaya 27:13)
@sa10) The shofar reminds us of the future resurrection of the dead and it
reaffirms our faith that God will revive the dead which will be heralded with
the sounding of the shofar.
@saThis Psalm (47) is recited seven times prior to the sounding of the Shofar.
The Name, @hh<HEB>€Œ„‰@ee<ENG>, which refers to God’s manifestation, as One Who rules
with strict justice, appears in this psalm seven times. Thus we mention the
Name @hh<HEB>€Œ„‰@ee<ENG> forty-nine times as a prelude to the sounding of the Shofar. Our
sages have said that there are forty-nine levels of spiritual impurity before
one reaches the lowest depth, from which no salvation is possible. On the
other hand, there are forty-nine ascending levels of intellectual sanctity
which man can attain. In reciting this psalm we pray for the blast of the
Shofar to arouse God’s mercy to overcome His manifestation of strict justice.
We also pray for the sound of the shofar to inspire us to climb from the
forty-ninth level of spiritual impurity, to rise to the forty-ninth level of
sanctity.
